  "prompt": "What instrument is used to measure volume?",
  "response": "The instrument used to measure volume can vary depending on the state of the substance (liquid or solid) and the level of precision required. For liquids, the most common instruments include:\n\n1. **Graduated Cylinder** - A cylindrical container with markings to measure the volume of a liquid accurately.\n2. **Beakers and Flasks** - Used for approximate volume measurements.\n3. **Pipettes and Burettes** - Used for precise volume measurements in laboratory settings.\n4. **Volumetric Flasks** - Used for preparing solutions at a precise volume.\n\nFor solids, particularly irregularly shaped ones, volume can be measured by water displacement, where the volume of the solid is equal to the volume of water displaced when the object is submerged.\n\nFor gases, volume measurement typically requires containers of fixed known volume, along with pressure measurements if precise gas volumes under various conditions are needed.",
